tools_called.args:
{"query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of captive rearing and subsequent reintroduction of bumblebees into the wild?", "summary": "The evidence regarding captive rearing and reintroduction of bumblebees shows mixed results with significant challenges documented across multiple trials. 

Captive rearing has been attempted with varying degrees of success: 22 trials from 13 countries have documented captive rearing using different methods including confining mated queens alone, with workers, or following CO2 anaesthetisation (Action 50). Success varies significantly by species - trials successfully induced spring queens of half-black bumblebee B. vagans and some yellow-banded bumblebees B. terricola to rear adults in captivity, but all three trials attempting to rear yellow bumblebee B. fervidus failed as queens laid eggs but larvae died before becoming adults (Action 50). Similar failures occurred with rusty-patched bumblebee and American bumblebee B. pensylvanicus (Action 50). Over four years of artificial rearing, Bombus terrestris queens gradually decreased in weight (Action 50).

For reintroduction success, seven replicated trials monitored laboratory-reared bumblebee colonies introduced to the environment (Action 52). In four trials where colonies developed until new queens were produced or the founding queen died, two trials (both in the UK) produced very low numbers of queens or zero, while two trials produced good numbers of new queens (Action 52). Social parasitism by cuckoo bees presents a significant challenge, with variable rates ranging from 0% in five trials to high rates of 25-66% and 79% in trials from Canada and the UK respectively (Action 52). Parasitism was reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate rather than very high nectar and pollen availability and releasing late rather than early in the season (Action 52). Supplementary feeding showed mixed results - improving reproductive success in one Canadian trial but showing no effect on colony productivity in a USA trial (Action 52).", "action_ids": ["50","52","53"]}

